{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"The first idea I'd like to suggest is that we all"},{"time":2000,"text":"love music a great deal. It means a lot to us."},{"time":5000,"text":"But music is even more powerful if you don't just listen to it, but you make it yourself."},{"time":11000,"text":"So, that's my first idea. And we all know about the Mozart effect --"},{"time":14000,"text":"the idea that's been around for the last five to 10 years --"},{"time":17000,"text":"that just by listening to music or by playing music to your baby [in utero],"},{"time":21000,"text":"that it'll raise our IQ points 10, 20, 30 percent."}]},{"cues":[{"time":25000,"text":"Great idea, but it doesn't work at all."},{"time":28000,"text":"So, you can't just listen to music, you have to make it somehow."},{"time":31000,"text":"And I'd add to that, that it's not just making it,"},{"time":35000,"text":"but everybody, each of us, everybody in the world"},{"time":37000,"text":"has the power to create and be part of music in a very dynamic way,"},{"time":41000,"text":"and that's one of the main parts of my work."},{"time":43000,"text":"So, with the MIT Media Lab, for quite a while now,"},{"time":45000,"text":"we've been engaged in a field called active music."},{"time":47000,"text":"What are all the possible ways that we can think of"},{"time":49000,"text":"to get everybody in the middle of a musical experience,"},{"time":52000,"text":"not just listening, but making music?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":55000,"text":"And we started by making instruments for some of the world's greatest performers --"},{"time":58000,"text":"we call these hyperinstruments -- for Yo-Yo Ma, Peter Gabriel, Prince,"},{"time":61000,"text":"orchestras, rock bands. Instruments where they're all kinds of sensors"},{"time":65000,"text":"built right into the instrument, so the instrument knows how it's being played."},{"time":68000,"text":"And just by changing the interpretation and the feeling,"},{"time":71000,"text":"I can turn my cello into a voice, or into a whole orchestra,"},{"time":74000,"text":"or into something that nobody has ever heard before."}]},{"cues":[{"time":77000,"text":"When we started making these, I started thinking, why can't we make"},{"time":79000,"text":"wonderful instruments like that for everybody,"},{"time":81000,"text":"people who aren't fantastic Yo-Yo Mas or Princes?"},{"time":85000,"text":"So, we've made a whole series of instruments."},{"time":87000,"text":"One of the largest collections is called the Brain Opera."},{"time":90000,"text":"It's a whole orchestra of about 100 instruments,"},{"time":92000,"text":"all designed for anybody to play using natural skill."},{"time":95000,"text":"So, you can play a video game, drive through a piece of music,"},{"time":98000,"text":"use your body gesture to control huge masses of sound,"},{"time":101000,"text":"touch a special surface to make melodies, use your voice to make a whole aura."},{"time":106000,"text":"And when we make the Brain Opera, we invite the public to come in,"},{"time":108000,"text":"to try these instruments and then collaborate with us"},{"time":111000,"text":"to help make each performance of the Brain Opera."},{"time":112000,"text":"We toured that for a long time. It is now permanently in Vienna,"},{"time":115000,"text":"where we built a museum around it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":117000,"text":"And that led to something which you probably do know."},{"time":120000,"text":"Guitar Hero came out of our lab,"},{"time":121000,"text":"and my two teenage daughters and most of the students at the MIT Media Lab"},{"time":124000,"text":"are proof that if you make the right kind of interface,"},{"time":127000,"text":"people are really interested in being in the middle of a piece of music,"},{"time":131000,"text":"and playing it over and over and over again."}]},{"cues":[{"time":134000,"text":"So, the model works, but it's only the tip of the iceberg,"},{"time":137000,"text":"because my second idea is that it's not enough just to want"},{"time":140000,"text":"to make music in something like Guitar Hero."},{"time":143000,"text":"And music is very fun, but it's also transformative."},{"time":146000,"text":"It's very, very important."},{"time":147000,"text":"Music can change your life, more than almost anything."},{"time":150000,"text":"It can change the way you communicate with others,"},{"time":152000,"text":"it can change your body, it can change your mind. So, we're trying"},{"time":155000,"text":"to go to the next step of how you build on top of something like Guitar Hero."},{"time":159000,"text":"We are very involved in education. We have a long-term project"},{"time":162000,"text":"called Toy Symphony, where we make all kinds of instruments that are also addictive,"},{"time":166000,"text":"but for little kids, so the kids will fall in love with making music,"},{"time":170000,"text":"want to spend their time doing it, and then will demand to know how it works,"},{"time":173000,"text":"how to make more, how to create. So, we make squeezy instruments,"},{"time":176000,"text":"like these Music Shapers that measure the electricity in your fingers,"},{"time":180000,"text":"Beatbugs that let you tap in rhythms -- they gather your rhythm,"},{"time":183000,"text":"and like hot potato, you send your rhythm to your friends,"},{"time":185000,"text":"who then have to imitate or respond to what your doing --"},{"time":188000,"text":"and a software package called Hyperscore, which lets anybody use lines and color"},{"time":192000,"text":"to make quite sophisticated music. Extremely easy to use, but once you use it,"},{"time":196000,"text":"you can go quite deep -- music in any style. And then, by pressing a button,"},{"time":200000,"text":"it turns into music notation so that live musicians can play your pieces."}]},{"cues":[{"time":206000,"text":"We've had good enough, really, very powerful effects with kids"},{"time":209000,"text":"around the world, and now people of all ages, using Hyperscore."},{"time":212000,"text":"So, we've gotten more and more interested in using these kinds of creative activities"},{"time":216000,"text":"in a much broader context, for all kinds of people"},{"time":218000,"text":"who don't usually have the opportunity to make music."},{"time":221000,"text":"So, one of the growing fields that we're working on"},{"time":222000,"text":"at the Media Lab right now is music, mind and health."},{"time":225000,"text":"A lot of you have probably seen Oliver Sacks' wonderful new book called"},{"time":228000,"text":"\"Musicophilia\". It's on sale in the bookstore. It's a great book."},{"time":232000,"text":"If you haven't seen it, it's worth reading. He's a pianist himself,"},{"time":234000,"text":"and he details his whole career of looking at and observing"},{"time":238000,"text":"incredibly powerful effects that music has had on peoples' lives in unusual situations."}]},{"cues":[{"time":243000,"text":"So we know, for instance, that music is almost always the last thing"},{"time":246000,"text":"that people with advanced Alzheimer's can still respond to."},{"time":250000,"text":"Maybe many of you have noticed this with loved ones,"},{"time":252000,"text":"you can find somebody who can't recognize their face in the mirror,"},{"time":254000,"text":"or can't tell anyone in their family, but you can still find a shard of music"},{"time":257000,"text":"that that person will jump out of the chair and start singing. And with that"},{"time":261000,"text":"you can bring back parts of people's memories and personalities."},{"time":263000,"text":"Music is the best way to restore speech to people who have lost it through strokes,"},{"time":267000,"text":"movement to people with Parkinson's disease."},{"time":269000,"text":"It's very powerful for depression, schizophrenia, many, many things."}]},{"cues":[{"time":273000,"text":"So, we're working on understanding those underlying principles"},{"time":275000,"text":"and then building activities which will let music really improve people's health."},{"time":279000,"text":"And we do this in many ways. We work with many different hospitals."},{"time":282000,"text":"One of them is right near Boston, called Tewksbury Hospital."},{"time":285000,"text":"It's a long-term state hospital, where several years ago"},{"time":287000,"text":"we started working with Hyperscore and patients with physical and mental disabilities."},{"time":291000,"text":"This has become a central part of the treatment at Tewksbury hospital,"},{"time":295000,"text":"so everybody there clamors to work on musical activities."},{"time":299000,"text":"It's the activity that seems to accelerate people's treatment the most"},{"time":303000,"text":"and it also brings the entire hospital together as a kind of musical community."},{"time":307000,"text":"I wanted to show you a quick video of some of this work before I go on."},{"time":352000,"text":"Video: They're manipulating each other's rhythms."},{"time":354000,"text":"It's a real experience, not only to learn how to play and listen to rhythms,"},{"time":358000,"text":"but to train your musical memory and playing music in a group."},{"time":363000,"text":"To get their hands on music, to shape it themselves, change it,"},{"time":367000,"text":"to experiment with it, to make their own music."},{"time":369000,"text":"So Hyperscore lets you start from scratch very quickly."},{"time":380000,"text":"Everybody can experience music in a profound way,"},{"time":382000,"text":"we just have to make different tools."}]},{"cues":[{"time":401000,"text":"The third idea I want to share with you is that music, paradoxically,"},{"time":407000,"text":"I think even more than words, is one of the very best ways we have"},{"time":410000,"text":"of showing who we really are. I love giving talks, although"},{"time":414000,"text":"strangely I feel more nervous giving talks than playing music."},{"time":416000,"text":"If I were here playing cello, or playing on a synth, or sharing my music with you,"},{"time":419000,"text":"I'd be able to show things about myself that I can't tell you in words,"},{"time":424000,"text":"more personal things, perhaps deeper things."}]},{"cues":[{"time":427000,"text":"I think that's true for many of us, and I want to give you two examples"},{"time":430000,"text":"of how music is one of the most powerful interfaces we have,"},{"time":433000,"text":"from ourselves to the outside world."},{"time":435000,"text":"The first is a really crazy project that we're building right now, called"},{"time":439000,"text":"Death and the Powers. And it's a big opera,"},{"time":441000,"text":"one of the larger opera projects going on in the world right now."},{"time":445000,"text":"And it's about a man, rich, successful, powerful, who wants to live forever."},{"time":450000,"text":"So, he figures out a way to download himself into his environment,"},{"time":452000,"text":"actually into a series of books."},{"time":455000,"text":"So this guy wants to live forever, he downloads himself into his environment."},{"time":458000,"text":"The main singer disappears at the beginning of the opera"},{"time":462000,"text":"and the entire stage becomes the main character. It becomes his legacy."}]},{"cues":[{"time":466000,"text":"And the opera is about what we can share, what we can pass on to others,"},{"time":469000,"text":"to the people we love, and what we can't."},{"time":471000,"text":"Every object in the opera comes alive and is a gigantic music instrument,"},{"time":475000,"text":"like this chandelier. It takes up the whole stage. It looks like a chandelier,"},{"time":478000,"text":"but it's actually a robotic music instrument."},{"time":480000,"text":"So, as you can see in this prototype, gigantic piano strings,"},{"time":484000,"text":"each string is controlled with a little robotic element --"},{"time":487000,"text":"either little bows that stroke the strings, propellers that tickle the strings,"},{"time":492000,"text":"acoustic signals that vibrate the strings. We also have an army of robots on stage."},{"time":497000,"text":"These robots are the kind of the intermediary between the main character, Simon Powers,"},{"time":501000,"text":"and his family. There are a whole series of them, kind of like a Greek chorus."},{"time":505000,"text":"They observe the action. We've designed these square robots that we're testing right now"},{"time":510000,"text":"at MIT called OperaBots. These OperaBots follow my music."},{"time":513000,"text":"They follow the characters. They're smart enough, we hope,"},{"time":516000,"text":"not to bump into each other. They go off on their own."},{"time":519000,"text":"And then they can also, when you snap, line up exactly the way you'd like to."},{"time":525000,"text":"Even though they're cubes, they actually have a lot of personality."}]},{"cues":[{"time":534000,"text":"The largest set piece in the opera is called The System. It's a series of books."},{"time":538000,"text":"Every single book is robotic, so they all move, they all make sound,"},{"time":542000,"text":"and when you put them all together, they turn into these walls,"},{"time":546000,"text":"which have the gesture and the personality of Simon Powers. So he's disappeared,"},{"time":551000,"text":"but the whole physical environment becomes this person."},{"time":554000,"text":"This is how he's chosen to represent himself."},{"time":557000,"text":"The books also have high-packed LEDs on the spines. So it's all display."},{"time":564000,"text":"And here's the great baritone James Maddalena as he enters The System."},{"time":568000,"text":"This is a sneak preview."},{"time":593000,"text":"This premieres in Monaco -- it's in September 2009. If by any chance you can't make it,"},{"time":598000,"text":"another idea with this project -- here's this guy building his legacy"},{"time":601000,"text":"through this very unusual form, through music and through the environment."},{"time":605000,"text":"But we're also making this available both online and in public spaces,"},{"time":609000,"text":"as a way of each of us to use music and images from our lives"},{"time":613000,"text":"to make our own legacy or to make a legacy of someone we love."},{"time":616000,"text":"So instead of being grand opera, this opera will turn into what we're"},{"time":619000,"text":"thinking of as personal opera."}]},{"cues":[{"time":621000,"text":"And, if you're going to make a personal opera, what about a personal instrument?"},{"time":623000,"text":"Everything I've shown you so far -- whether it's a hyper-cello for Yo-Yo Ma"},{"time":626000,"text":"or squeezy toy for a child -- the instruments stayed the same and are valuable"},{"time":631000,"text":"for a certain class of person: a virtuoso, a child."},{"time":634000,"text":"But what if I could make an instrument that could be adapted"},{"time":637000,"text":"to the way I personally behave, to the way my hands work,"},{"time":641000,"text":"to what I do very skillfully, perhaps, to what I don't do so skillfully?"},{"time":644000,"text":"I think that this is the future of interface, it's the future of music, the future of instruments."}]},{"cues":[{"time":649000,"text":"And I'd like now to invite two very special people on the stage,"},{"time":652000,"text":"so that I can give you an example of what personal instruments might be like."},{"time":658000,"text":"So, can you give a hand to Adam Boulanger, Ph.D. student from"},{"time":663000,"text":"the MIT Media Lab, and Dan Ellsey. Dan,"},{"time":670000,"text":"thanks to TED and to Bombardier Flexjet, Dan is here with us today"},{"time":677000,"text":"all the way from Tewksbury. He's a resident at Tewksbury Hospital."},{"time":681000,"text":"This is by far the farthest he's strayed from Tewksbury Hospital, I can tell you that,"},{"time":685000,"text":"because he's motivated to meet with you today and show you his own music."},{"time":690000,"text":"So, first of all, Dan, do you want to say hi to everyone and tell everyone who you are?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":699000,"text":"Dan Ellsey: Hello. My name is Dan Ellsey. I am 34 years old and I have cerebral palsy."},{"time":707000,"text":"I have always loved music and I am excited to be able to conduct"},{"time":713000,"text":"my own music with this new software."}]},{"cues":[{"time":717000,"text":"Tod Machover: And we're really excited to have you here, really Dan. (Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":728000,"text":"So we met Dan about three years ago, three and a half years ago,"},{"time":731000,"text":"when we started working at Tewksbury. Everybody we met there was fantastic,"},{"time":736000,"text":"did fantastic music. Dan had never made music before, and it turned out"},{"time":741000,"text":"he was really fantastic at it. He's a born composer."},{"time":748000,"text":"He's very shy, too."},{"time":751000,"text":"So, turned out he's a fantastic composer, and over the last few years has been"},{"time":755000,"text":"a constant collaborator of ours. He has made many, many pieces."},{"time":758000,"text":"He makes his own CDs. Actually, he is quite well known in the Boston area --"},{"time":761000,"text":"mentors people at the hospital and children, locally, in how to make their own music."},{"time":765000,"text":"And I'll let Adam tell you. So, Adam is a Ph.D. student at MIT, an expert in music"},{"time":770000,"text":"technology and medicine. And Adam and Dan have become close collaborators."},{"time":775000,"text":"What Adam's been working on for this last period is not only how to have Dan"},{"time":779000,"text":"be able easily to make his own pieces,"},{"time":782000,"text":"but how he can perform his piece using this kind of personal instrument."},{"time":785000,"text":"So, you want to say a little bit about how you guys work?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":787000,"text":"Adam Boulanger: Yes. So, Tod and I entered into a discussion"},{"time":790000,"text":"following the Tewksbury work and it was really about how Dan is an expressive"},{"time":794000,"text":"person, and he's an intelligent and creative person. And it's in his face,"},{"time":799000,"text":"it's in his breathing, it's in his eyes. How come he can't perform"},{"time":802000,"text":"one of his pieces of music? That's our responsibility, and it doesn't make sense."}]},{"cues":[{"time":806000,"text":"So we started developing a technology that will allow him with nuance,"},{"time":809000,"text":"with precision, with control, and despite his physical disability, to be able to do that,"},{"time":814000,"text":"to be able to perform his piece of music."},{"time":817000,"text":"So, the process and the technology --"},{"time":819000,"text":"basically, first we needed an engineering solution. So, you know,"},{"time":822000,"text":"we have a FireWire camera, it looked at an infrared pointer."},{"time":825000,"text":"We went with the type of gesture metaphor that Dan was already used to"},{"time":829000,"text":"with his speaking controller."},{"time":833000,"text":"And this was actually the least interesting part of the work, you know,"},{"time":836000,"text":"the design process. We needed an input; we needed continuous tracking;"},{"time":839000,"text":"in the software, we look at the types of shapes he's making."}]},{"cues":[{"time":842000,"text":"But, then was the really interesting aspect of the work, following the engineering part,"},{"time":846000,"text":"where, basically, we're coding over Dan's shoulder at the hospital"},{"time":849000,"text":"extensively to figure out, you know, how does Dan move?"},{"time":852000,"text":"What's useful to him as an expressive motion?"},{"time":854000,"text":"You know, what's his metaphor for performance?"},{"time":857000,"text":"What types of things does he find"},{"time":859000,"text":"important to control and convey in a piece of music?"},{"time":861000,"text":"So all the parameter fitting, and really the technology"},{"time":865000,"text":"was stretched at that point to fit just Dan."},{"time":868000,"text":"And, you know, I think this is a perspective shift. It's not that our technologies --"},{"time":874000,"text":"they provide access, they allow us to create pieces of creative work."},{"time":878000,"text":"But what about expression? What about that moment when an artist delivers"},{"time":881000,"text":"that piece of work? You know, do our technologies allow us to express?"},{"time":885000,"text":"Do they provide structure for us to do that? And, you know, that's a personal relationship"},{"time":889000,"text":"to expression that is lacking in the technological sphere. So, you know,"},{"time":893000,"text":"with Dan, we needed a new design process, a new engineering process"},{"time":896000,"text":"to sort of discover his movement and his path to expression that allow him to perform."},{"time":901000,"text":"And so that's what we'll do today."}]},{"cues":[{"time":903000,"text":"TM: So let's do it. So Dan do you want to tell everyone"},{"time":905000,"text":"about what you're going to play now?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":913000,"text":"DE: This is \"My Eagle Song.\""},{"time":917000,"text":"TM: So Dan is going to play a piece of his, called \"My Eagle Song\"."},{"time":920000,"text":"In fact, this is the score for Dan's piece,"},{"time":922000,"text":"completely composed by Dan in Hyperscore."},{"time":925000,"text":"So he can use his infrared tracker to go directly into Hyperscore."},{"time":930000,"text":"He's incredibly fast at it, too, faster than I am, in fact."}]},{"cues":[{"time":933000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":937000,"text":"TM: He's really modest, too."},{"time":940000,"text":"So he can go in Hyperscore. You start out by making melodies and rhythms."},{"time":946000,"text":"He can place those exactly where he wants."},{"time":948000,"text":"Each one gets a color. He goes back into the composition window,"},{"time":951000,"text":"draws the lines, places everything the way he wants to. Looking at the Hyperscore,"},{"time":956000,"text":"you can see it also, you can see where the sections are,"},{"time":959000,"text":"something might continue for a while, change, get really crazy and then end"},{"time":964000,"text":"up with a big bang at the end."}]},{"cues":[{"time":967000,"text":"So that's the way he made his piece, and as Adam says,"},{"time":970000,"text":"we then figured out the best way to have him perform his piece."},{"time":977000,"text":"It's going to be looked at by this camera, analyze his movements,"},{"time":980000,"text":"it's going to let Dan bring out all the different aspects of his music that he wants to."},{"time":984000,"text":"And you're also going to notice a visual on the screen."},{"time":987000,"text":"We asked one of our students to look at what the camera is measuring."},{"time":993000,"text":"But instead of making it very literal, showing you exactly"},{"time":996000,"text":"the camera tracing, we turned it into a graphic that shows you the basic"},{"time":1001000,"text":"movement, and shows the way it's being analyzed."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1005000,"text":"I think it gives an understanding of how we're picking out movement from what"},{"time":1009000,"text":"Dan's doing, but I think it will also show you, if you look at that movement,"},{"time":1013000,"text":"that when Dan makes music, his motions are very purposeful, very precise,"},{"time":1020000,"text":"very disciplined and they're also very beautiful."},{"time":1023000,"text":"So, in hearing this piece, as I mentioned before, the most important thing is"},{"time":1028000,"text":"the music's great, and it'll show you who Dan is."},{"time":1031000,"text":"So, are we ready Adam?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1033000,"text":"AB: Yeah."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1035000,"text":"TM: OK, now Dan will play his piece \"My Eagle Song\" for you."},{"time":1183000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1207000,"text":"TM: Bravo."},{"time":1209000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}